-LsXty7eDbnTQrHvffjr.howMeasured:
Land Use Classes in England

A1 Shops and retail outlets (not including those uses listed under Sui Generis)
A2 Professional and financial services (not including health and medical services)
A3 Cafes and restaurants
A4 Drinking establishments
A5 Hot food outlets and takeaway

B1a Offices
B1b R&D labs
B1c Light industrial

B2 General Industrial Use
B8 Storage or distribution

C1 Hotels, guest houses and boarding houses 
C2 Residential institutions (including care homes, hospitals, residential schools and colleges)

C3a Dwellings – Single family or 'household'
C3b Shared home - Up to 6 people
C3c Single household groups - Up to 6 people
C4 Houses in multiple occupation (3-6 people)

D1 Non-residential institutions
D2 Assembly and leisure

Sui Generis (including betting offices, pay day loans shops, theatres, large HMOs, hostels scrap yards, petrol stations, laundrettes, car showrooms, wholesalers, nightclubs, taxi businesses and casinos.

-LsXty7eDbnTQrHvffjt.policyRef: Town and Country Planning (Use Classes) Order 1987
-LsXty7eDbnTQrHvffjt.howMeasured:
'Family Home' covers use by a single person or a family (a couple whether married or not, a person related to one another with members of the family of one of the couple to be treated as members of the family of the other).

 It can also include an employer and certain domestic employees (such as an au pair, nanny, nurse, governess, servant, chauffeur, gardener, secretary and personal assistant), a carer and the person receiving the care and a foster parent and foster child, or a group of people living together as one household (for example a religious community)

A 'Shared Home' (known as a House in Multiple Occupation or HMO) is a house or flat in which 3 or more people are living who belong to different families/households, and share kitchen, bathroom or toilet facilities. You can read more on this definition [here](https://www.gov.uk/private-renting/houses-in-multiple-occupation).

-LsXty7gFS3aZ7pYDzYR.text: Does the original house have a projection to the rear?
-LsXty7gFS3aZ7pYDzYR.howMeasured:
A projection or 'outrigger' is a part of the building that protrudes out, so the building forms a T or L shape. Some houses may have more than one. In some cases projections may themselves have a projection, creating a stepped shape.

The original house is the house as it was first built; not including any later additions.

-LsXty7gFS3aZ7pYDzYT.text: It will extend beyond the back wall of the original house by
-LsXty7gFS3aZ7pYDzYT.info: On designated land, structures that extend more than 4m from the rear wall of a detached house will required planning permission.
-LsXty7gFS3aZ7pYDzYT.howMeasured: The depth of an extension is measured from the external face of the rear wall of the 'Original' house. So this dimension includes any prior extension that may have been added to the house. It does not include any guttering or barge boards.

-LsXty7gFS3aZ7pYDzYX.text: It will extend beyond the back wall of the original house by
-LsXty7gFS3aZ7pYDzYX.info: On designated land, structures that extend more than 4m from the rear wall of a detached house will required planning permission.
-LsXty7gFS3aZ7pYDzYX.howMeasured:
The depth of an extension is measured from the external face of the rear wall of the 'Original' house. So this dimension includes any prior extension that may have been added to the house. It does not include any guttering or barge boards.

If the rear of the original house is 'stepped', this distance should be measured from the respective facing part of the rear wall, not from another part of the rear wall that may extend further to the rear of the property.

-LsXty7iY-us7Jrq5YTW.info:
Any extension that extends beyond the front wall which forms the principal elevation of the dwellinghouse will require planning permission.  

If you are at all unsure as to which side of the house is the principal elevation, you should consult a planning officer.
-LsXty7iY-us7Jrq5YTW.howMeasured:
This is measured as if there were an imaginary line across the front of the principal elevation of the house, extending all the way to the property boundary. You should not include bay windows, protrusions or previous additions.

The principal elevation usually means that side of the house which fronts (directly or at an angle) the main highway serving the house (the main highway will be the one that sets the postcode for the house concerned). It will usually (but not always) contain the main architectural features such as main bay windows or a porch serving the
main entrance to the house. 

In some cases (for example a house on a corner, or a house that appears to face sideway) it is not clear which is the principal elevation.

The 'original' house is the house as it was when first built, not including any extensions or outbuildings that have been added since.

'Additions' include any enclosed structure in the grounds of the house, including decks, garden sheds, greenhouses, other storage buildings, swimming pools or other pools or containers (such as tanks).

-LsXty7iY-us7Jrq5Ya6.info: Planning permission will be required if any part of the new building is situated forward of the front elevation of the original house.
-LsXty7iY-us7Jrq5Ya6.howMeasured:
This is measured as if there were an imaginary line across the front of the principal elevation of the house, extending all the way to the property boundary. You should not include bay windows, protrusions or previous additions.

The 'front' in this case means the principal elevation. The principal elevation usually means that side of the house which fronts (directly or at an angle) the main highway serving the house (the main highway will be the one that sets the postcode for the house concerned). It will usually (but not always) contain the main architectural features such as main bay windows or a porch serving the main entrance to the house. 

In some cases (for example a house on a corner, or a house that appears to face sideway) it may not be clear which is the principal elevation. If unsure, you should consult your local planning authority.

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKC.text: What kind of antenna will it be?

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKG.text: In total, the property will have
-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKG.info: Antennae includes both aerials or satellite dishes. Development requires planning permission if it would result in more than two antennae on the building or within the same property.

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKI.text: The length of the antenna will be
-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKI.info: Length is measured in any linear direction, and excludes any projecting feed element, reinforcing rim, mounting or brackets. Planning permission is required for any antennae longer than 1m.

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKM.text: The length of the largest one will be
-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKM.info: If there will be two antenna, only one may be longer than 0.6m. The other may not exceed 1m in length. Length is measured in any linear direction, and excludes any projecting feed element, reinforcing rim, mounting or brackets.

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKP.text: The length of the smallest one will be
-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKP.info: If there will be two antenna, only one may be longer than 0.6m. The other may not exceed 1m in length. Length is measured in any linear direction, and excludes any projecting feed element, reinforcing rim, mounting or brackets.

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKT.text: Does the house have a chimney?

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKV.text: Will an antenna be installed onto the chimney?

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKX.info: Planning permission is required if an antenna installed on a chimney is longer than 0.6m.

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBK_.text: Will any part of an antenna be higher than the chimney?
-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBK_.info: Height is measured from the highest point of the chimney. Planning permission is required if any antenna installed on a chimney would protrude above the chimney.

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKc.info: Planning permission is required if any part of the antenna would be higher than the top of the chimney, or 0.6m above the highest part of the roof, whichever is lower.
-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKc.howMeasured: Measured from the highest point of the antenna, and the highest point of the roof (excluding any chimneys)

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKd.text: more than 0.6m higher than the roof

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKf.text: less than 0.6m higher than the roof

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKi.text: The highest part of any antenna will be
-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKi.info: Roof height is measured to the highest part of the roof.  Planning permission is needed for any antenna that is mounted higher than this.

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKk.text: the same height as the roof

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKm.text: The cubic capacity of all antennae will be
-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKm.info: If after adding the antenna the cubic capacity of all antenna would be more than 35 litres, planning permission would be required.
-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKm.howMeasured: Cubic capacity is the width x depth x height as measured at the maximum point of each.  All dimensions exclude any projecting feed element, reinforcing rim, mounting or brackets.

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKp.text: Is the property on designated land?
-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKp.info: Designated land (also known as 'Article (2) 3' land) is any of: land in a Conservation Area; land in an Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty; Land affected by the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981, land in the Broads, land in a National Park, or land that is part of a World Heritage Site.

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKr.text: Would any antenna be mounted on a surface visible from a highway?
-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKr.info: On designated land, planning permission will be required for any antenna that would be mounted onto any chimney, wall or roof slope that faces onto or is visible from a highway.
-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKr.howMeasured: Highway includes roads, pavements, public pathways and bridlepaths.

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKu.text: Is the property in the broads?

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKw.text: Would any antenna be mounted on a surface visible from a waterway?
-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBKw.info: In the broads, planning permission will be required if the antenna would be mounted onto any chimney, wall or roof slope that is visible from a waterway.

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBL-.text: The height of the building is
-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBL-.info: On designated land, planning permission will be required if the antenna would be mounted onto a buildin that exceeds 15m in height.

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBL3.text: Was your house always a house?

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBL6.info: Planning permission will be required if the right to use the property as a dwelling has been granted only by Permitted Development (Change of Use)

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBLB.text: Sorry, Plan✕ doesn't support the installation of aerials to flats or non-residential properties yet.

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBLD.text: Will the antenna be situated so as to minimise impact on the appearance of the building?
-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBLD.info: An antenna on a building must (as far as is practical), be situated so as to minimise its effect on the external appearance of the building.

-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBLG.text: The antenna must be removed when it is no longer needed
-LsXty7jl8lNaQtMVBLG.info: If the antenna is no longer needed for reception or transmission purposes will it be removed as soon as reasonably practicable

-LsXty7kZOaSK_D3jKdY.info:
Planning permission is required if the total capacity of all solar PV equipment on the property would exceed 1 megawatt. 


If the total capacity is less than 1MW, but more than 50kW, it will require Prior Approval in writing from your local planning authority, who will assess it on the basis of its potential impact on neighbouring properties and the local area, in particular for example, potential for glare.
GPDO 2015 P.14 J.4 (2)

PV units with a capacity of less than 50kW are defined as 'Microgeneration' according to the Energy Act 2004.
